<body>
<div class="container">

  <!-- Header -->
  <header>
    <div class="breadcrumb">EE LAB JOURNAL / <span>2024</span> / DIGITAL LOGIC</div>
    <h1>Building a <em>BCD Adder</em><br/>on a Breadboard</h1>
    <div class="meta">
      <span class="meta-item">Digital Logic</span>
      <span class="meta-item">Hardware Debugging</span>
      <span class="meta-item">74HC/LS Series ICs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag">74HC283</span>
      <span class="tag">CD4511BE</span>
      <span class="tag">7-Segment Display</span>
      <span class="tag">DIP Switch</span>
      <span class="tag">MB102 Power Supply</span>
      <span class="tag">BCD Correction Logic</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- What I Built -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">01 — What I Built</div>
    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Built a fully functional BCD (Binary Coded Decimal) adder on a breadboard that takes two valid BCD numbers (0–9 each) as inputs via DIP switches, adds them together using cascaded 74HC283 4-bit adders, and displays the units digit on a 7-segment display with a separate LED indicating the tens carry (i.e. whether the sum is ≥ 10).
    </p>
    <p>
      The circuit includes BCD correction logic using 74LS AND/OR gates — necessary because a raw binary adder can produce values 10–15 which are invalid in BCD. When the sum exceeds 9, the correction stage adds 6 (binary 0110) to skip the invalid hex range and produce a valid two-digit BCD result.
    </p>

    <div class="component-grid">
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">2× 74HC283</div>
        <div class="component-desc">4-bit binary adders. U1 adds the raw inputs; U4 applies BCD correction (+6 when sum > 9).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">CD4511BE</div>
        <div class="component-desc">BCD-to-7-segment decoder. Drives the display directly from the corrected sum bits.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">7-Segment Display</div>
        <div class="component-desc">Common cathode display showing the units digit of the BCD sum (0–9).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">74LS08 + 74LS32</div>
        <div class="component-desc">AND and OR gates implementing the correction trigger logic.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">8-position DIP Switch</div>
        <div class="component-desc">Two 4-bit BCD inputs (A and B), one nibble per switch bank.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="component-card">
        <div class="component-name">LED + Resistor</div>
        <div class="component-desc">Tens indicator — lights when carry-out from U4 goes HIGH (sum ≥ 10).</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Signal flow -->
    <div class="signal-flow">
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">INPUT</span>
        <span class="fb-name">DIP Switches</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">U1</span>
        <span class="fb-name">74HC283 Adder</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">U3/U4 Gates</span>
        <span class="fb-name">Correction Logic</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">U4</span>
        <span class="fb-name">74HC283 +6</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">U5</span>
        <span class="fb-name">CD4511 Decoder</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-block">
        <span class="fb-label">OUTPUT</span>
        <span class="fb-name">7-Seg + LED</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Problems & Solutions -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">02 — Problems Encountered & Solutions</div>
    <h2>Debugging Log</h2>
    <p>This build had a surprisingly deep chain of hardware issues. Here is every problem encountered and how it was resolved.</p>

    <div class="problem-list">

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-01</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Power supply set to 3.3V instead of 5V</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-high">CRITICAL</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>The MB102 breadboard power supply module has two yellow jumpers — one per rail — that select between 3.3V and 5V output. Both were set to 3.3V. The CD4511BE and 74HC/LS logic chips all require 5V; at 3.3V they enter an undefined operating region and behave unpredictably.</p>
          <p>Symptom: LT and BL pins on CD4511 measured only <code>3.2V</code> despite being wired to the supply rail. All segment outputs were incorrect.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Moved both MB102 jumpers to the 5V position. Also discovered the breadboard has split power rails (top and bottom halves are independent) — added two bridging wires to connect top and bottom + rails and top and bottom GND rails.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-02</span>
          <span class="problem-title">DIP switch commons not connected to 5V</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-high">CRITICAL</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>The 5V supply side of all 8 DIP switch positions was left completely unconnected. With no voltage source on one side, the switches had nothing to drive the signal lines HIGH when toggled. All inputs floated at ~<code>1.97V</code> — mid-rail noise — regardless of switch position.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Connected the common (supply) side of all 8 switch positions to the 5V rail. With switch OFF the pull-down resistor holds the line LOW; with switch ON, 5V drives the line HIGH through the switch.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-03</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Wrong pull-down resistor value causing switch leakage</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-high">HIGH</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>Initially used 22KΩ resistors (misread from kit), then switched to 10KΩ as specified. However the CTS 526 DIP switches have measurable leakage current when OFF. With 10KΩ pull-downs, this leakage produced ~<code>1.7V</code> on signal lines when switches were open — right at the 74HC283 logic threshold of 1.5V, causing random behaviour.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Replaced all pull-down resistors with 1KΩ. The lower resistance aggressively pulls the leakage current to ground, bringing the OFF voltage down to a safe ~<code>0.5V</code> — well below the logic LOW threshold.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-04</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Faulty resistors from kit (open circuit internally)</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-med">MEDIUM</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>Multiple resistors from the component kit were found to be internally broken — they measured correct resistance on the colour bands but showed open circuit (<code>OL</code>) on the multimeter in resistance mode. This caused some pull-down nodes to remain floating even when the resistor appeared correctly inserted.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Always test resistors out-of-circuit in resistance mode before inserting. Measure both legs — a good 10KΩ resistor reads ~10,000Ω. Discard any that read OL or significantly out of spec.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-05</span>
          <span class="problem-title">CD4511 LT/BL pins not reaching logic HIGH threshold</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-high">HIGH</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>The CD4511BE has three control pins: LT (Lamp Test, pin 3), BL (Blanking, pin 4), and LE (Latch Enable, pin 5). LT and BL must be tied HIGH (5V) and LE must be tied LOW (GND) for normal operation. When LT is LOW, it overrides all inputs and forces every segment ON — which caused segment G to appear active and confused initial debugging.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Verified and corrected pin 3 and pin 4 connections to the 5V rail; pin 5 to GND. After power supply was fixed to 5V, these pins read correctly and the decoder started functioning normally.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-06</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Segment G burned out from initial setup without resistors</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-med">MEDIUM</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>During the initial circuit setup, the 7-segment display was briefly connected without current-limiting resistors on the segment lines. Segment G (the middle horizontal bar) was driven directly and burned out. This made digits 2–6 and 8–9 display incorrectly, causing significant confusion during debugging since those digits all require segment G.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Replaced the 7-segment display. Always install current-limiting resistors (330Ω) on every segment line before applying power. Test each segment individually with a known good voltage + resistor before wiring to the decoder.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-item">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">P-07</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Multimeter probe acting as antenna on floating pins</span>
          <span class="problem-severity sev-low">LOW</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <p>When probing pins that were floating (not driven HIGH or LOW), touching them with the multimeter probe caused the display to change randomly. The probe tip was capacitively coupling noise into the high-impedance floating node, making it appear as if the measurement itself was changing the circuit.</p>
          <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-label">→ FIX</div>
            <p>Floating inputs are a diagnostic red flag — if the multimeter probe changes the circuit, the node is not properly driven. The fix is always to ensure every input pin is tied definitively to either 5V or GND, never left floating.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Lessons -->
  <section>
    <div class="section-label">03 — Key Lessons Learned</div>
    <h2>Takeaways</h2>

    <div class="lessons-grid">

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">⚡</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Always verify supply voltage first</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Before debugging any logic issue, measure VCC and GND at every chip. A sagging or wrong supply voltage causes symptoms that look like logic errors but aren't.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">🔌</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Floating inputs are the enemy</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Any unconnected input on a CMOS or TTL chip will float to an unpredictable voltage. Every input pin must be tied to a defined logic level — even unused ones.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">🧪</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Test components before inserting</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Resistors, LEDs, and even ICs can be dead out of the bag. Use resistance mode on the multimeter to verify resistors before insertion. Test LEDs with a coin cell.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">📐</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Pull-down value matters for real switches</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Real DIP switches have leakage current when open. A 10KΩ pull-down may not be strong enough — 1KΩ is safer for clean logic levels near GND when the switch is OFF.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">🔍</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Trace signals systematically</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Debug by measuring at every stage in the signal chain — input → adder → correction → decoder → display. The point where voltage stops being correct is exactly where the fault is.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">🛡️</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Resistors before LEDs, always</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Never connect an LED directly to a logic output without a current-limiting resistor. Without it, LEDs will burn out instantly. 220–330Ω is standard for 5V logic.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">🔋</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Breadboard power rails are split</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">Long breadboards have power rails that are physically split in the middle. Always add bridging wires between both halves of the + rail and GND rail, or components on opposite ends won't share the same supply.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-card">
        <span class="lesson-icon">📖</span>
        <div class="lesson-title">Read the datasheet control pins</div>
        <p class="lesson-body">The CD4511 has three control pins (LT, BL, LE) that override normal operation if left floating. Always check the datasheet for control/enable pins and tie them to their correct idle state.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
